<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Sounds_and_orthography">Sounds and orthography</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Consonant_and_vowel_phonemes">Consonant and vowel phonemes</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Ethiopian_Air_aircraft_showing_Ethiopic_script.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/Ethiopian_Air_aircraft_showing_Ethiopic_script.jpg/220px-Ethiopian_Air_aircraft_showing_Ethiopic_script.jpg" width="220" height="188" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Ethiopian_Air_aircraft_showing_Ethiopic_script.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/skins-1.17/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The Ethiopic (or Ge'ez) writing system is visible on the side of this <a href="/wiki/Ethiopian_Airlines" title="Ethiopian Airlines">Ethiopian Airlines</a> <a href="/wiki/Fokker_50" title="Fokker 50">Fokker 50</a>: it reads "Ethiopia's": የኢትዮጵያ (ye-Ītyōṗṗyā).</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>There is no agreed way of transliterating Amharic into Roman characters. The Amharic examples in the sections below use one system that is common, though not universal, among linguists specializing in Ethiopian Semitic languages. The Amharic ejectives correspond to the <a href="/wiki/Proto-Semitic" title="Proto-Semitic" class="mw-redirect">Proto-Semitic</a> "<a href="/wiki/Emphatic_consonants" title="Emphatic consonants" class="mw-redirect">emphatic consonants</a>", usually transcribed with a <a href="/wiki/Dot_(diacritic)" title="Dot (diacritic)">dot</a> below the letter. The consonant and vowel charts give these symbols in parentheses where they differ from the standard <a href="/wiki/International_Phonetic_Alphabet" title="International Phonetic Alphabet">IPA</a> symbols.</p>
